teacher_thoughts: I think about experience, they have went through a lot of training and teaching to be able to teach college students the material of interest.
metaphor_think: Ideally a teacher should be like a tour guide, they ought to be able to make the material they are teaching accessible and interesting to the students, so they can be motivated and interested to learn from them like tourists would from a tour guide.
metaphorother: They are vocal and articulate, able to voice their thoughts clearly without being misunderstood.

The teacher like the coach ideally needs to identify the needs of the students, becoming available to them outside class, like in office hours to reinforce teaching or clarify concepts.

Metaphor_justify: Out of the other metaphors, this one sounds the most accurate. A gardener must take careful measures to ensure their garden of plants grow, flourish, and strive in a diverse set of conditions. The same logic can be applied to a (AMAZING) teacher. In order for a student to grow and strive under unexpected real world problems, it's the job of the educator to guide and arm the student with tools to tackle any adversity they face. The gardener does the same by carefully using the correct soil, PH level, sunlight/shade, appropriate amount of water, etc. What distinguishes a decent gardener from an AMAZING gardener is the ability to understand that each plant may require a different set of conditions. For example, a cucumber plant may need more water than lavender. The same can be applied to the students. A student may need a bit more guidance with close instruction while another may simply need to be left alone and work at their own pace.

Q93_A: Cool study. Thanks for the fair pay

teacher_thoughts: Somebody who is a very knowledgeable person or an expert on a specific subject. Maybe a bit arrogant, but generally well informed and a valuable person to get to know.
metaphor_think: A student visits an institution like a university to learn, and while neither the teacher or students permanently reside there, the teacher is the one explaining the subject/place to the students in a way in which they can learn.
Metaphor_justify: The teacher is the person who nurtures their class' intellectual capacities. At the start, the plants need a lot of help, but as the plants grow, they begin to blossom without needing everything given to them. The teacher is responsible for taking care of the students when they are starting out, and although I believe students have a lot of responsibility, they cannot be expected to know anything about the subject prior to starting the class. This metaphor just seems better than something as ephemeral as a tour guide / tourist relationship.

teacher_thoughts: Somebody who has a master's degree or higher and instructs college students in a college course. They may be a professor or just an instructor.
metaphor_think: A teacher can be a tour guide by showing students information on the subject and guiding them through the journey of learning. Students are like tourists because they observe and listen to their teacher, the tour guide.
Metaphor_justify: Teachers in college can't force students to learn or take the course seriously. They provide the necessary information to learn, but it's up to the students to absorb it and use it.

teacher_thoughts: When I think of a college teacher I think of hard work and dedication. A college teacher is skilled and tested.
metaphor_think: A teacher can be compared to a tour guide and students tourists because teachers are there to guide you on your journey. They are teaching you and helping you learn new ideas and information to help you in the world.

teacher_thoughts: I think about lectures. i think about teachers being the only one that speak and students just listening

metaphor_think: A teacher could show students the fun and exciting aspects of their discipline, taking the students "on a tour" through the various aspects of their area of focus.

A coach also puts his/her players in the best position to succeed; likewise, a teacher may help his/her students succeed by giving them the individual attention they need to thrive.

teacher_thoughts: A college teacher is usually an expert in something, a professor who does research on something related to the topic they teach
metaphor_think: A teacher is like a tour guide because he or she has knowledge of something that the students don't know. Metaphor_justify: This metaphor captures the individual role that students have in their own learning. Teachers are able to provide guidelines and information, but students must gradually take on the role of learning on their own. Teachers have expertise, but students can, through work, gain a similar level of expertise.

teacher_thoughts: I think about my college teachers and how helpful and passionate they were about teaching their subjects.
metaphor_think: A teacher is like a tour guide because they guide students who are the unfamiliar tourists through learning a subject.

teacher_thoughts: I think of a strict person with deadlines that don't budge. The teacher tries to relay information and help when they can even if they are strict.
metaphor_think: A teacher is like a tour guide in the way that they introduce new ideas and things to the students. The students listen like tourists and are paying the 'tour guide' to share their knowledge.
metaphorother: Teachers inspire others to love subjects/places
Metaphor_justify: I like the metaphor because I am an artist myself. Teachers start with a base, a student willing to learn. The students are clay. The teachers, depending on their skill levels, can mold beautiful master pieces or just lumps of clay. It all depends on how skilled the teacher is and how easy to work with the student is. The students have to be receptive to being molded but the teacher is still the one making art.

teacher_thoughts: I think of someone with a masters degree and confidence in their field. or I think of someone who is a graduate student getting credits.

"Personally, I had always been interested in nature in general. Making the teacher as a metaphor for something that nurtures their students was a bit heartfelt. 
That and this metaphor pretty much places a lot of responsibility to the students' learning."

teacher_thoughts: A college teacher is an advanced worker in society. They teach young adults different facets of life and advanced techniques and materials.
metaphor_think: A teacher is there to guide you through the course and life. The students are there to follow the tour guide and learn from them. The tour guide is the teacher as stated in teh example.
metaphorother: I can't think of any at the moment
Metaphor_justify:
"I believe this is the best metaphor. College students are new to being adults and college teachers have a responsibility to shape them into well-functioning adults. Some parents don't teach their kids responsibility, but college teachers will with demanding deadlines and great discussion points. 

In my experience, college professors always pushed me to be better. They taught me many things about their specific subject. I feel like I was the clay and the teacher shaped me into a beautiful piece of art. "

teacher_thoughts: I generally think about someone who is snooty and intellectual. They often value their subject matter or expertise higher than it should be regarded.
metaphor_think: A teacher is very knowledgeable on their subject matter or expertise as a tour guide is familiar with his/her city or location. A teacher tried to impart as much knowledge on the students, similar to how a tour guide is supposed to leave you with more information.

teacher_thoughts: College teachers are what lead this great nation into the future. They spread their knowledge to students to lead us into the future generations.
metaphor_think: A teacher leads their students into the future be teaching them about grooming them into  decent human beings.

teacher_thoughts: They are generally well read and have a lot of knowledge in their field of study. They also like to read a lot.
metaphor_think: A teacher like a tour guide shows the tourists or students the information they are to learn just as a tour guide shows tourists exhibits etc.

experience_free: I have a masters degree in speech language pathology and have taught students with disabilities for 2 years.

teacher_thoughts: The person is in his/her mid 40's. Drinks coffee, is very articulate and passionate on his/her subject.

teacher_thoughts: More advanced, striving to teach at a higher level of learning. More intelligent than lower level teachers.

metaphorother: teachers inspire students to seek information

teacher_thoughts: I think of someone who is older and wears a vest, or maybe a sweater. They are intelligent, but not necessarily good at teaching their subject.

teacher_thoughts: i feel that college teachers are more free in their teaching sometimes. I think of personal responsibility more with college teachers than others.
metaphor_think: because they are just showing you were to look and its up to you to decide what you want to take out of the experience.

teacher_thoughts: I think a college teacher moves beyond the high school expectation of rote memorization, to a position of helping you on your own journey toward learning, providing a reinforcing role to the books, lab activities and other more independent learning a college environment develops.
metaphor_think: College is an adventure -- in high school, almost everyone is on the same track, to the same destination. Once we get to college, we're off exploring new fields and deciding where we want to spend the rest of our careers; this exploration is guided by the professors as tour guides, showing us what can be down each path and leading us toward a major and a degree.
metaphorother: College teachers encourage students to learn for themselves
Metaphor_justify: I believe that college itself is a time for exploration and finding one's own path. The professors serve as tour guides by showing the most important learning in a subject of the student's own choosing, compared to a student's earlier development along a set path through elementary school (developing as people, more like the garden metaphor) or high school (developing basic rote memorization and thinking skills, like the coach).  And just like a vacation to the wrong destination, the tour guides can and will show you everything important about the wrong thing, if you choose the wrong major (which I did in college)
experience_free: I was a TA and recitation leader for mechanical engineering classes in years 3, 4 and 5, teaching a lab course and twice weekly study sessions.

metaphor_think: College teachers take knowledge from a broad spectrum of sources and condense them down into information that is needed for their students. SO college teachers take their students through they highlights of a certain subject area and the students take notes on the information given.

experience_free: I've been in education classes, and taught a couple of science lessons to middle and high school students.

teacher_thoughts: College teachers, or professors, are quite astute in my opinion. They seem to really love learning and are always seeking knowledge themselves. They are more up for debate with their students.
metaphor_think: I agree with this statement. It speaks to how college teachers have the vast knowledge about a certain subject and are there to help their eager students learn all that they need and want to know.

However, like a coach-athlete relationship, the coach will give you what you need to perform well, but it is up to you to apply what you have learned to succeed.

teacher_thoughts: When I think of a college teacher, I think of someone more open minded with different ways of teaching a variety of students. I think of someone that is a good speaker and able to connect with even a larger group of students.
metaphor_think: I definitely agree with this metaphor because the college teacher is experienced in what they are teaching in terms of hands on experience as well as a lot of knowledge and the students are just beginning to go into that field and learning new things exactly how a tourist would be in a new place with a tour guide. They not only teach the subject but teach the ins and outs of working in that particular field.
metaphorother: Teachers are able to present somewhat boring or mundane information and make it a lot more interesting and interactive.
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this metaphor because it feels the most accurate without over or understating the importance of a college teacher and their impact on students. A gardener plants seeds, waters and feeds them and helps them grow, much like a college teacher with their students. However, a gardener can help the plant grow and try different ways to make sure they turn out great, but they can't force it and they can't guarantee what the plant will end up like, also much like college teachers. They can guide, influence and give much to their students but students will not all be the same and will not all come out perfect.

Q93_A: This was definitely an interesting survey and unlike ones I've done. I enjoyed the aspect of being able to freely type my thoughts rather than just answering multiple choice or rating type questions.

teacher_thoughts: I think of a "professor", not a "teacher". This professor has a PhD or a similar degree in his or her field and has respect.
metaphor_think: I disagree with this metaphor (although it's actually a simile, not a metaphor), but I would say it could be that the student is just passing through the course and could move on if they don't like it while the teacher "lives" in the material day in and day out over many years.
metaphorother: Teachers can inspire students to stay in their field longer
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this analogy because you can be completely self-taught and still be a genius, just like you can have no formal professional coaching experience and be a natural.  However, it's very difficult and rare for this to happen, as formal training is typically the best way.  Following with this analogy, you have to train on your own outside of your coach's training, and eventually you can become a coach, too, when you are skilled and knowledgable enough.
Q93_A: Similes use "like" or "as" in their comparisons, whereas metaphors do not; these were similes, not metaphors.

teacher_thoughts: Someone who gets paid to indoctrinate people. They are effectively useless now that we have the internet.
metaphor_think: I guess the teacher can show the students different things that they wouldnt have come across elsewhere. In that respect then they are useful.
metaphorother: It really depends. These are broad generalizations and they differ from teacher to teacher.
Metaphor_justify: They just try to change you, especially the ones with strong leftist politics. Youre literally getting paid to be brainwashed.

teacher_thoughts: I think of someone who is very well-versed in their field and wants to pass down this knowledge to continue an academic legacy
metaphor_think: I like this one, as students are charting unfamiliar territory and the teacher is guiding them through the obstacles to gain familiarity.
Metaphor_justify: I really like this one, as I said before. In college I never really felt like my professors were molding or shaping me. But they were providing me with the information that would be necessary for me to become knowledgeable in the field of my choosing.

teacher_thoughts: College teachers generally are very diverse in their personality but all have a very strong passion for what they teach as well as seem to be rather good at it if they are teaching in front of potentially hundreds of students.
metaphor_think: I really feel this is accurate in a lot of ways. In many ways the professor is like a tour guide on the safari that is a particular course.
Metaphor_justify: I feel that a teacher helps that individual grow in knowledge and understanding and this metaphor really helped to describe that.

teacher_thoughts: someone who is an expert in an specific area and who is willing to share their knowledge with others
metaphor_think: I think it is right, in some way, a teacher leads the path the students then follow, he or she must know this path in order to teach it to the students
Metaphor_justify: I always use this metaphor, when we start college, we are nothing but clay, and this experience is what is going to sculpt us into what we will be as professionals

teacher_thoughts: In my experience, college teachers are fast-paced and generally do not delve deep into topics -- rather, they introduce them and it is the student's job to examine them further. Additionally, college teachers and professors expect a great deal of time to be spent on their teachings outside of the classroom (ie. attending office hours, writing lengthy reports that require weeks of work, etc.). To me, college teaching is equivalent to independent learning.
metaphor_think: I think it means that the teacher is knowledgeable and familiar with a topic like a tour guide would be. It is the teacher's job to relay the important aspects of this topic to the students (much like how a tour guide provides information to tourists).
metaphorother: Generally, I imagine a parallel between tour guides and college teachers can be made about how their presentations are very structured/rehearsed as opposed to conversational/impromptu.
Metaphor_justify: I think this is more realistic of real life. Some people thrive and "bloom" even under the most unskilled of gardeners; likewise, even an expert gardener sometimes encounters a dying plant. I think this places even responsibility for learning on both the teacher and the student.
experience_free: I was a peer TA (meaning I taught undergraduate students while I myself was still an undergraduate) for freshman-level engineering courses for multiple semesters.
Q93_A: I think this was a very interesting survey!

teacher_thoughts: College teachers are very educated. They have to be very organized because they teach a lot of students at once.
metaphor_think: I think that the metaphor means that the teacher are the tour guides to adulthood. They are kind of showing students, in a way, that their education is now their responsibility, and no one is going to be there to hold their hand anymore.
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this metaphor because a teacher can not do things for the students, like a coach. A coach can tell and show his team how to do things, but it is up to them to practice and get it.

teacher_thoughts: Generally, I think of an older person who has likely worked in the field they're teaching about for many years. I think of someone who has the drive to learn and to spread their knowledge and enjoys helping others understand their passions.
metaphor_think: I think this metaphor is particularly apt for professors who teach general education classes and introductory classes for various subjects. In these cases, students are often getting their feet wet with new ideas/topics and the professor is guiding a fairly surface-level exploration of that subject.
Metaphor_justify: Much like a coach, I find that college professors most importantly give students the tools and information they need to succeed. Professors, like coaches, cannot complete your work for you or personally force you somehow to be better at what you're doing/studying or even to complete work in the first place. Also like coaches, professors can kick you off the team (out of class) if you are consistently choosing to not perform to the best of your abilities and asking for the kind of help you need. Much like athletes, students are taking the tools and knowledge they get from their professors and applying it themselves. They have to put in the effort in order to make the material the professors teach them worth anything for them in the long run. In addition, much like a coach a professor can be a trusted confidant to whom a student can go when they are struggling - either with course material or with general life.

Some topics may be very focused and the student's future jobs or ability to work may depend on how well they absorb the material, as well as how well the teacher teaches. The teacher should know the material they are teaching, and be able to answer complex teachers that any students may pose.
metaphor_think: A teacher will take care of his plants and let his plants grow slowly, but surely. Plants will absorb many things, such as water and sunlight (class material)
Metaphor_justify: I feel as if, without the gardener, the plants will not be able to survive. Similarly, without a good teacher, the students will not "grow" to the best that they can, and in turn, affect the student's future. If, for example, the gardener does not take care of his plants, or does not care for his plants, then his plants won't absorb enough nutrition and wither away. Similarly, if students have a teacher that does not care for the students, the students won't learn anything, and when they go out to work in the real world, they won't know what to do.
Q93_A: quite an interesting survey. Thank you.

teacher_thoughts: I think of a very educated person.  Usually someone who is very interested about what they teach and wanting to show others how to be successful in the field or subject.
metaphor_think: Because a teacher provides students with resources in order for them to grow and learn.  The teacher helps them realize and express their inherent potential.
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this metaphor because I think it is the most accurate.  With the information that the teacher teaches, the students grow and learn from it.  They learn things that they did not know before.  It fits into my experiences because after learning  subject or class I feel much more developed and intelligent on the subject and like I have literally grown in ways.

teacher_thoughts: I think of someone who typically does lectures using slides. They probably have a teachers assistant that does their grading and most of the interaction with the students.
metaphor_think: College students come to college because they want to grow and develop into adults, College teachers are a key part of imparting them with knowledge in a way  nurturing it like a gardener would nurture a plant.
metaphorother: Teachers check in on their students well being outside of the classroom.
Metaphor_justify: I think a good teacher should show you possible ways of thinking and let you decide which ones you want to explore. For me the best teachers devote time in the class to hearing what we think about the material, which of the theories we agree with and why and allow us to disagree with the theories even when were being tested on them.
experience_free: I used to be a captain on my high school dance team and I would teach dances and technique to the other members of the team.

teacher_thoughts: Someone who is very well studied in the subjects they teach. They are the most highly educated in their field.
metaphor_think: College teachers are here to plant the seeds of curiosity, understanding, and drive in students who will hopefully someday sprout into masters of a field in their own right.
metaphorother: I can't think of any at the moment.
Metaphor_justify: The first metaphor deals with a sculptor creating something and molding something that is final and rigid. Tour guides only lead tourists in a temporary and fleeting sort of situation. Coaches are effectively teachers for athletes, so the metaphor involved with those labels just doesn't seem to sit right. The gardener and plants metaphor fits best as it implies that while a plant can grow best under the watchful eye of a gardener, the plant still grows and shapes itself continually. The last metaphor just has a more life-long feel to education, like any good metaphor should have.
experience_free: My teaching experience has been limited to multiple years as a undergraduate learning and graduate teaching assistant for science related classes.

teacher_thoughts: I think about someone educated who chooses to learn more instead of doing something more practical. They are very specialized in their field and know a lot.
metaphor_think: College teachers try to coax their students into growing and learning, but it is a delicate process that involves a lot of ingredients and every student reacts differently.
metaphorother: Teachers provide students with the tools they need to grow.
Metaphor_justify: I like this one because it emphasizes how students are the ones with the most agency and trying to gain the most from the experience. Teachers guide them, but students have just as much power and choice over their learning experience.

teacher_thoughts: A college teacher is someone who values learning. College teachers tend to be career learners who value education both in their own lives and the lives of others.
metaphor_think: Education is difficult and requires a great deal of attention and care. Students typically know less than the teacher in respect to a given topic. It is the job of a teacher to help cultivate the student's abilities into practical working knowledge.
Metaphor_justify: Education is very much like playing a team sport. The coach and the players are apart of the same team. They all are responsible for the success or failure of the team. The coach is the guide.

teacher_thoughts: Usually they are called Professors. Some are good at teaching and some aren't. They probably make a decent living.
metaphor_think: How well the students learn the material can vary with how well the teacher teaches it, similar to how well plants grow can vary with how well the gardener tends to it.
Metaphor_justify: A tour guide shows people around a new place and may give them idea of places to go or things to do they would not have known about otherwise, but does not dictate to them what they have to do. Ultimately, it's up to the tourists what they do and where they go when the tour is over. The teacher-student relationship is similar in that teachers will show students things they may not have thought of or known about otherwise, but it is up to the students what to do with that knowledge.

teacher_thoughts: I think of a person who is incredibly knowledgable in their field and well-versed in that subject area. I also think of someone who is able to easily explain concepts in a way that they are understandable.
metaphor_think: I believe this means that teachers help their students to grow and become successful, just as gardeners help their plants grow and achieve more.
Metaphor_justify: I believe that this metaphor more accurately reflects the reality that although teachers can provide guidance and instruction, students have to put their effort into learning and becoming better students, just as athletes have to put effort into becoming better athletes. You have to be willing to learn from teachers as a student, just as athletes have to be willing to be coached.

teacher_thoughts: first thing that comes to mind when I think college teacher is a professor with a robe and glasses on .
metaphor_think: I like the metaphor because it means a teacher places knowledge inside a students head to grow like a plant
Metaphor_justify: students is like seeds the gardener is the person that keep watering it and taking care of it until it turns into this beautiful plant of knowleage

teacher_thoughts: When I think of a college professor I think about someone who is passionate about a particular subject. I particularly think about my pwn professors who all seemed to me disorganized in some way or another.
metaphor_think: I teacher is like a gardener because they give you the things that one needs to grow and become stronger.
Metaphor_justify: I chose this metaphor because teacher do shape the minds of their students. They pour information into them that allows them to grow and become stronger in a particular area

teacher_thoughts: Laid back, professional but approachable. Willing to lend a hand if needed, but wants you to be more independent.
metaphor_think: I think college professors are the last stop before 'adulthood'. More of the 'cultivating' happens earlier on, but these are the last steps of the process. College professors are like chefs that pick plants from the garden to make a great dish from.
Metaphor_justify: I think this gives the students more accountability for their actions. It certainly fits the teachers I had in college.

teacher_thoughts: A person who knows a lot of things, and is willing to share that knowledge with others in a college setting.
metaphor_think: I think it means that a teacher tends to their students. Just like plants need food, water, and care, the student needs the materials. And like it's been shown that plants will grow better under good care, so do students.
Metaphor_justify: I prefer it because while the teacher does have to start things, it's really up to the student to grow their best self with help from the teacher. It doesn't really fit my experience since my teachers are barely present at all, but the idea of it is really nice. It would be nice to have that kind of support.

teacher_thoughts: i think college teachers are very dedicated to continuing their learnings. they have to keep up with changing times and new ideas.
metaphor_think: i think that it means that teachers help young and old students bloom, like a flower or a plant. by "bloom", i mean grow, prosper, and flourish.
Metaphor_justify: i prefer this metaphor, because with the one about plants, the plants dont really have free will as to how much they learn, or responsibility for that. but for athletes, they actually have to put in the work themselves, and a coach simply guides them.

teacher_thoughts: I think of a professor who has likely invested a lot of their time in learning in their field of discipline.
metaphor_think: I think this metaphor means a teacher is responsible for ensuring that the students are taken care of. A gardener tends to a garden and plants are a mainstay of a garden. Proper care of a plant helps it grow so a teacher is responsible for helping students grow.
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this metaphor because I find a lot of college students are in awe of their teacher's knowledge and tend to appeal to authority in their learning. Students tend to follow what their teacher teaches them which makes them like the clay that their teachers sculpt.
experience_free: My teaching experience is more like coaching where I have taught others how to utilize software systems efficiently.

teacher_thoughts: college teachers are the one who impact knowledge to the students  through any types of education like teaching,drilling or intuition for the purpose of bringing about positive changes to the students
metaphor_think: in this metaphor, teachers are represented with gardener because they are the one that do impact the knowledge they have to their students which are also represented with plants, here education serve as water in which the gardener(teachers) use in bringing about positive changes in the plants(students)
Metaphor_justify: this metaphor implies that the teacher as a coach make use of different methods in making positive or impacting positive changes in the students(athletes), such as drilling or training

teacher_thoughts: A professor, who gives you a lot less individual attention than high school teachers and for actual help on class work you need to show up after class to hopefully get some insight about how to do the class work
metaphor_think: It is a good metaphor because for the students to prosper, similarly to plants the teachers have to put in the time and energy to make sure they are nourished ( in this case the 'food' is the knowledge they provide)
metaphorother: Not that I can think of right now
Metaphor_justify: I like it more because it is not putting all the pressure on the teachers for the students success, and kind of mirrors the 'you can bring a horse to water but cant force it to drink'. The teachers are a critical part of providing students with new information they may not have learned otherwise but it is really up to the student to decide if its worth it to them to that a 'picture' and retain that knowledge for the future.

teacher_thoughts: I think about someone dedicated to education and research. I think of someone who is laid back and easygoing
metaphor_think: It means that a college teacher helps students grow and learn. A college teacher nourishes students through learning
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this metaphor because it shows that teacher are there to guide, but not mold students. On a tour, you can follow the tour guide and learn more, but you can also go off and learn more on your own. The tour guide gives you the resources to do that

teacher_thoughts: Someone who is very smart and has gone through many many years of learning things. they can be mean and strict
metaphor_think: It means that teachers shower us with their life experiences and knowledge and we grow just as flowers grow.
Metaphor_justify: I believe this one is more spot on because the way our teachers are is basically how sculptors mold clay into new things. Their teachings will mold us into the future
experience_free: I have taught a lab class in college and I have been a substitute teacher at the public schools in my city

teacher_thoughts: They are a like any other teacher except teaching on a higher level. I expect most of them to be more actively involved.
metaphor_think: Like a gardener, teachers help students grow, like plants. They are essentially helping build students up when they are at school.
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this metaphor sense it puts less emphasis on how much work the teacher does. From my perspective, teaching is a two way street. While a tour guide has a lot of information, it is up to the tourists to decide where they want to go and what to do with that information.

teacher_thoughts: My mind goes to the more unusual professors who have challenged the very ways I thought and forced me to understand the world in new ways.
metaphor_think: Some of the best teachers don't tech fact but how to think. For them teaching is planting seeds that with care can grow into new thought patterns.
Metaphor_justify: Students aren't passive. They grow in their own individual ways. However the pattern they grow in can be molded. Teaching and learning are collaborative processes that depend on both. Simple transfers of knowledge are not enough for deep understanding. True understanding requires the student to grow into it.

experience_free: I have tutored many students and have guest lectured 5 different courses for college students.

teacher_thoughts: Qualified personnel with a large amount of experience in a certain field. They are capable of relating the knowledge they know into a way that someone who doesn't know anything can understand.

teacher_thoughts: Often someone who is likely very qualified and interested in the subject, but overworked and underpaid. At some universities, they might not be too interested in teaching.
metaphor_think: Teachers can cultivate knowledge and watch students grow as they learn. Another idea is that a teacher could 'plant a seed' and watch the student grow, where the seed is knowledge.

teacher_thoughts: someone who is either trying very hard to help but doesn't necessarily have all of the tools for different kinds of students, or someone who is rigid and says you can sink or swim on your own.
metaphor_think: teachers can help students grow, but if they don't know how to help different kinds of people, like different kinds of plants, they don't grow as much or sometimes at all.

teacher_thoughts: A college professor is someone who is supposed to be fair, but tough as they teach students the next step in understanding complex topics within science or humanities classes. I generally liked all of my college professors after talking with them and getting to know them.
metaphor_think: Teachers provide information to students and this information is like "water" that helps the students grow like plants.
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this metaphor because I think it gives the students a little more agency and control over their teachings. The tour guide gives information and asks the tourists questions to spark debate, but they still control the group and are the authority figure, like  college professor. With the students though, they are able to ask questions and explore different ideas while taking in all the information. This is a better metaphor with the students than comparing them to flowers or clay where it seems like they are just absorbing information without doing anything with it.

teacher_thoughts: Inconsiderate and sanctimonious, those are two words i use to describe them. I think the re are good and bad ones.

teacher_thoughts: I think college teachers are very distinguished people in their fields and they work very hard doing more than just teaching.
metaphor_think: The college professor is like the master gardener, nurturing the students so they can blossom and grow. This metaphor makes sense to me.

experience_free: I work as a 7th grade science teacher currently, but no college teaching experience.

It's the same with the professor's relationship with the student. The professor presents the lecture, and it is the student's (me) responsibility to understand/absorb that knowledge. If the professor does not present his lecture well, I will have a hard time and die (inside) in the class because I couldn't absorb the presentation to the best of my knowledge.

teacher_thoughts: a middle aged person who teaches at a collage who may or may not be a professor. the teacher will usually have a degree in the subject that they are teaching.

teacher_thoughts: I think about a teacher that is an expert in their area, and ready to explain the subject to other adults.
metaphor_think: The students can only grow as much as the teacher is willing to provide for them, the information learned would be like water and sunlight.

teacher_thoughts: Someone who is guiding or teaching students the material (topic) at hand. They are trying to enable them to learn and further their development base on the subject at hand.
metaphor_think: The teacher is fostering the growth of her students. The more knowledge she show, the quicker they grow.

teacher_thoughts: I think of someone that has higher knowledge than the rest of the people in the classroom. This person is more knowledable just in certain topics.
metaphor_think: The teacher is like a gardener because he takes care of the plants. He is responsible for feeding knowledge into their minds.

teacher_thoughts: When I think of a college professor, I imagine stern and busy. I also picture them in front of a large group of students.
metaphor_think: The teacher, the gardener, is necessary for the student, the plant, to grow.  The teacher is essential for growth.

teacher_thoughts: A person who teaches college students and does their own research or work. They are employee by a college and usually have a PhD or Masters in their field.
metaphor_think: The teachers gives the students the nutrients (knowledge) needed to grow, just like a gardener provides food and nourishment for their plants.

teacher_thoughts: Most of my professors seem stern, no-nonsense, unforgiving. I dont really think they care about what may be going on in you life to make your grades go down they more so care about getting things done no matter the circumstance.
metaphor_think: The treat waters the student with the knowledge and as students we soak up the information as best as possible to get a better understanding.

teacher_thoughts: Being a college teacher is very different from being a primary school teacher; you don't necessarily need a degree in instruction to teach a subject.
metaphor_think: This analogy seems to have some parallels such as a teacher has to respond to a student's individual needs, just like a gardener has to care for each plant individually.

teacher_thoughts: What comes to my mind when I think about a college teacher is a college professor. Someone who is very smart, intelligent and knows how to do their job well.
metaphor_think: This is a great metaphor, it is saying that teachers have the knowledge and wisdom and they bestow it upon their students, Helping the students to learn, grow and become better. Just like a gardener does with plans.
Metaphor_justify: I like this one a lot because it fits teachers and students very well. A teacher is like a coach in the sense that they help, teach and only want the best for the student. Students are apart of a teachers team and teachers usually love and adore them, just like a coach does.

teacher_thoughts: I think about someone who is experienced and well-learned in the field that they teach. They are smart and have an ability to share knowledge regarding their field.
metaphor_think: This means that the teacher must nourish, watch over and take care off their students so that they are able to grow and reach their full potential.
metaphorother: No, not that I can think of.
Metaphor_justify: A teacher is like a tour guide because they show students the material they are teaching lesson by lesson, much like a tour guide shows tourists from room to room. The tour guide can stop to answer questions from those that want to know more, just like a teacher when a student asks a question. However, in the end no matter how much the tour guide talks and shows it is up to the tourists to pay attention and take in the information they are learning about much like students do. No matter how good the tour guide is their will always be some tourists who do not pay attention, just like with students.

teacher_thoughts: When I think of someone who is a professor I think of someone who is knowledgable and approachable. They are someone who is the type of person that will take the time to explain a difficult concept.
metaphor_think: This metaphor makes sense because students can only expand their knowledge like a plant grows. Plants can be fine on their own, kind of like students, but a good gardner can make them florish, like a good professor.
Metaphor_justify: I believe that students have an inherent level of talent and that they could reach things on their own but with the assistance of a good coach they can unlock their total potential.

teacher_thoughts: A college teacher is a person who is there to teach you about a certain topic that you will need to be successful.
metaphor_think: This metaphor means that the teacher's job is to take care and make sure the students grow successfully.
Metaphor_justify: I prefer this metaphor because I see the average teacher more as a guide. They are there to show you the way but it's ultimately up to tourists or students to follow the guide or teacher.

metaphor_think: A college teacher is like a sculptor in the sense that they are metaphorically molding the student with content and knowledge from a subject to become the image or masterpiece the teacher wants to witness from the student. experience_free: I have taught preschoolers and have been a teaching assistant for a psychology class in high school.

experience_free: As a teacher, I had to find several ways to teach the same concept to different students. It was challenging but rewarding.

teacher_thoughts: When I think about a college teacher I think about academic professionals who are experts in their fields and tend to have a particular area of interest. I think they're generally passionate about their work and want students to succeed, but are also under a lot of pressure.
metaphor_think: Students are like clay because they are waiting to be molded, and the teacher shapes them to what they want them to be. In other words, the teacher tells the students what to think/believe.
Metaphor_justify: I think this metaphor represents teachers as helping their students learn and grow, but not forcing them in any one direction. A gardener doesn't control what color flower the plants have or what direction they grow in. Plants can sprout or not sprout with the best or worst gardener - there is more left up to chance than in the sculptor metaphor. Likewise, college teaching should encourage students to grow (give them the tools they need, like a gardener gives plants sunlight and water) without forcing their own ideas and hopes onto the students. Like the gardener doesn't control the way the plant appear, a college teacher should not control the way students think or express themselves.

teacher_thoughts: Professional, well-read. Someone who knows every little detail about a specific topic. A literature teacher has read everything you've ever read and stuff you've never heard of, a math teacher knows how the 3rd derivative of location was used in the engineering of the Hubble space telescope, a history teacher knows the color of George Washington's underwear. Know-it-alls but in the best possible way. A little odd sometimes; sometimes you have to be a little odd to devote yourself so completely to a topic.
metaphor_think: Teachers are like sculptors because they shape the knowledge of a student. By being the source of information for students, teachers control and influence (almost) everything their students learn on a topic. Students are like clay because the influence of the sculptor causes their thoughts to take form.
metaphorother: Teachers work to create professionals from students.
Metaphor_justify: I picked this metaphor because it made me think of a museum, when you're being shown around and told things. They usually introduce the subject, but it's still up to you to read the plaque/information on the display. I think college is like this. The teachers can tell you things, provide the general information, but if you really want to master the subject, you need to read the plaque/ask the tour guide questions. I liked the flower metaphor because I thought it was a pretty example of how teachers help us grow, but I thought this was more honest. Teachers guide us (like a tour guide) through a subject and it's up to us to pick up the little things they are telling us and to branch into the areas that we want to know more about either through research or asking questions.

I think the teacher and gardener are similar in that they both help and use their experience to improve the plant or the student. In my experience I feel that a teacher has always been there to take the talents that I already have and make them better and more useful.
